In an emergency call, the professor confessed to shooting his girlfriend.
During a call to the emergency line with a trembling voice, Professor Shannon Lamb confessed to the police that he had shot his girlfriend and it was necessary for them to come to their home.
Lamb vowed that his "sweet dog" was alive and probably upset at the house, and that contacts on the dead woman's family could be found on her phone.
Inside, police found Amy Prentiss's body and a handwritten message on white office paper: "I'm so sorry and I wish I could return it, I loved Amy and she's the only one who ever loved me," the letter said.
There was no suspicion that Lamb, who taught two online courses for Delta State University in Cleveland, Mississippi, would drive 300 miles to a school campus where police believe he shot the popular Professor Ethan Schmidt at the door of his office.
Delta State University Police Chief Lynn Buford said the university staff heard the shooting at 10:18 a.m.
Lamb reportedly made a fateful call to the emergency line shortly after.
Finally, another death came; Lamb took his own life when the police came for him.
The day after the school shooting forced students and faculty to hide behind locked doors, the authorities are still trying to find out what Lamb's motivation was.
The details, published by state investigators and students and employees who knew him, together created the image of a talented but probably troubled teacher.
The students confirmed that they were looking forward to his lessons.
The police in Gautier, where Prentiss died, confirmed that he had no criminal record or violent past.
Schmidt himself included Lamb in the book he wrote, in a thank-you to the "great people" with whom he shared his academic life.
Both taught at the Faculty of Social Sciences and History, along with 17 other faculty members, and many students attended classes at both at the same time.
At the same time, there were inclinations in terms of problems.
A student who praised Lamb, Brandon Beavers, said he also seemed agitated and shaken, "as if something was wrong with him."
Another student, Mikel Sykes, said Lamb told him he was dealing with stress at the end of the 2014-15 academic year.
Lamb had previously asked Delta State University for a medical leave, saying he had a problem.
And this year he taught only two online courses.
Recent changes to the university's recruitment of staff meant that a doctorate, for which Lamb worked hard, would not guarantee him an automatic term of office to become an assistant professor.
University President William LaForge said he was not aware of any conflict between Lamb and Schmidt, but that "Mr. Lamb seems to have been troubled."
Lamb will no longer answer these questions.
After leaving the campus, police caught his trail as he crossed the state border into Arkansas back to Mississippi.
Before he could be arrested, Lamb killed himself with a single gunshot in the yard of a house about a mile from his parents in the suburb of Greenville, Mississippi, Washington State Coroner Methel Johnson confirmed.
He left the car on the street.
It was not immediately clear why Lamb was going to this house, although Johnson said he probably knew the people who lived here.
Lamb grew up in this area.
Lamb began working at the university, which has 3,500 students in the city, which has about 12,000 inhabitants, in 2009 and taught geography and hours of education.
In the spring he received his doctorate in education.
One of Lamb's longtime friends described him as a smart, charismatic and funny man.
