She was with her friends in high school and he was the great older boy who taught her guitar for several years.
He was a heartbreaker at the time.
The hearts of all the girls were softened as soon as he appeared,” said Hairston, who is now 40 years old and lives in the suburbs of Jackson.
Lamb and Prentiss reportedly dated for a while.
During an emergency call, Lamb said, "I killed my wife," but the wedding record never existed.
They had a dog named Lightning, who lived with them in a brick house adjacent to the shoulder of the Gautier River.
Police said the dog was fine.
Prentiss's ex-husband, Shawn O'Steen, said they broke up 15 years ago but remained friends and had a daughter, who is now 19 years old.
"It was a total breakdown," O'Steen said of his daughter.
She and her mother were best friends.
O'Steen said he hadn't met Lamb, but through his daughter Abigail he knew that Lamb was interested in music and played blues.
Lamb met Prentiss when he and Abigail performed at the summer festival three years ago.
Later, they played random gigs together.
O’Steen said his daughter was writing and singing her own music.
Prentiss was a nurse who worked for various online companies.
Mike Shaffer, bartender and occasional entertainment coordinator at The Julep Room, a dimly lit bar near Gautier, said he last saw Lamb and Prentiss on the night of September 5, the sweat that Lamb finished on guitar and harmonica for a small crowd.
There was no sign of anything wrong.
"He was just a happy couple," he said.
We were chatting and recording each other for a joke.
I mean, they both had a good sense of humor.
Schmidt, a murdered professor, led a first-year seminar and specialized in original American and colonial history, said Don Allan Mitchell, an English professor at the school.
He was married and had three small children.
He studied at Emporia State University in Kansas and was president of the boys' student club and student government.
At the Delta State campus in Cleveland on Tuesday night, about 900 people, including faculty members, staff, students, and community members, attended a commemoration event with candles.
Schmidt's wife Liz, and brother Jeff Schnidt also attended the vigil, during which the university choir sang "Bright Morning Star" and "Amazing Grace."
School started again on Wednesday.
"We're trying to get our students back," LaForge says.
The crisis is behind us.
