Multiple sclerosis: it is not only about the drugs, but also about the patient's will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: a neurologist, a physiotherapist, an occupational therapist, a urologist, an ophthalmologist, a psychologist, a psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, this is not only about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations, if they decide to have a child, social legal advice, recommendations for housing, etc.
However, all this is not enough: the development of the disease can significantly affect the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and does not have to fundamentally change the style of his life.
As doctors point out, the passiveness of the patients frees up space for the activity of the disease.
For example, it is proved that regular movement significantly delays the time when the patient needs some compensatory aid, for example, a stick.
It is important that patients and their surroundings do not succumb to various myths, for example that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
This is why the Give a Chance website (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give a Chance.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
For multiple sclerosis, there is a saying that the sooner the disease begins to heal, the more likely a doctor can influence something.
This is because we have drugs for multiple sclerosis in the inflammatory stage, when the process of neurodegeneration is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater is the hope that we will be able to stop the disease and delay the disability, explains Dr. Eva Medov<0xC3><0xA1> from the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
It is very important for people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often solves the weakening of the lower limbs or imbalance.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, relieve swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It is really individual, depending on the specific difficulties of the patient," says MUDr. Martina Köv<0xC3><0xA1>ri, Head of the Clinic of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine at the Faculty Hospital in Motol.
Although people with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, it manifests itself in a slightly different way for everyone.
Rehabilitation can not stop the disease, but it can always relieve its symptoms.
However, physical activity also strengthens the immune state of the body, which is desirable in case of multiple sclerosis.
Another benefit of regular exercise is the fact that the patients check what they can do, and this strengthens their self-confidence.
"The endorphins are also released during the exercise and the person feels well after it," says PhDr. Kamila <0xC5><0x98>asov<0xC3><0xA1> from the Clinic of Rehabilitation Medicine of the Faculty Hospital of Kr<0xC3><0xA1>lovské Vinohrady.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We directly intervene in the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, he adds.
"In the past, these patients were so-called "saved", today we know that they need a targeted load," says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kol<0xC3><0xA1><0xC5><0x99>, Head of the Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine Clinic at the Faculty Hospital in Motol.
The goal of physiotherapy is to ensure that a person can remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including employment.
Physiotherapists therefore cooperate with occupational therapists so that each person receives a compensatory aid tailor-made for him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They are in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people are shaken by it.
They experience shock, panic, fear.
They have to respond to a heavy burden - loss of health.
With such a sore soul, we have to follow someone, not try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them so that they can finally come to the conclusion that even with a disability it is possible to live a full-fledged life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinov<0xC3><0xA1> - Schubertov<0xC3><0xA1> from the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
Without the Prague manufacturer Latecoere, the Airbuses would not fly.
Aircraft production is synonymous with precision and advanced technology.
The new aircraft are full of titanium or light and solid composite materials that no one can make and process.
Nevertheless, in addition to super-precise, computer-controlled machine tools, in addition to autoclaves for forming composites, one can come across something as ordinary as apricot kilns.
In the drum, which resembles a sugar wool pot, the edges of the sheet metal parts that have just come out of the milling machine are ground in the pile of furnaces.
"No one has come up with anything better yet," smiles Ivan Dubsk<0xC3><0xBD>, CEO of the latecoere Czech Republic aircraft door manufacturer.
At the premises in Prague’s Let<0xC5><0x88>any, the former Letov produces complete doors for the Airbus A320.
They are the only ones in the world to supply the doors for the Brazilian Embraer 170.
The door, part of which is being assembled in Prague, also includes passengers in the first and upper class on the upper decks of the world’s largest transport aircraft, the Airbus A380.
There are also doors full of composites for the new Boeing 787 Dreamliner.
Accuracy is the main motto here.
For example, the momentary keys are adjusted twice a year by the company.
If the yellow sticker does not have a check record, they should explain to the auditors from Airbus or Boeing, who drive regularly to see if the doors are made according to the agreed rules, in the Prague plant.
Human senses, however, have not yet been completely replaced by advanced technology.
There are 1,500 rivets on one door to the A320.
The rivets must be cracked by hand.
It takes them two days.
Even from the sound of the hammer falling, they can tell if the rivet is already correctly broken.
The tolerance in which they move is minimal.
The nit can rise above the surface of the aircraft from zero to 0.13 millimeters.
That's about twice the thickness of a human hair.
During the inspection, a trained touch comes to the fore.
When the controller swipes a string of rivets with his finger, he knows if there is any out-of-tolerance.
Then he takes the exact deflection meter in his hand.
Letov lived before 1989 the program of the training military aircraft L-39.
In 1991, none of them were made.
The company had to find new jobs quickly.
At that time, it teamed up with the European aircraft manufacturer Airbus.
She won a tender for an emergency door supplier for the A321.
Conversations with Boeing were not so happy.
“We were a small company for them at the time, which did not have enough money to invest and to guarantee Boeing long-term stable deliveries,” Dubsk<0xC3><0xBD> recalls.
The door to the American manufacturer would remain closed if Letov did not take the French group Latecoere at the Prague conference of the international aviation industry association in 1999.
I talked about our cooperation with Airbus.
Negotiations with the French began the next day, Dubsk<0xC3><0xBD> said.
A year later Latecoere bought the Czech company and with a strong company came new orders.
In 2000, the assembly of door parts for the A320 began.
Three years later, the upper deck doors for the A380 were added.
In 2006, the company built a new composite processing hall for deliveries to the Boeing Dreamliner.
Without Latecoere, we would not have gotten to these big jobs on our own.
Maybe we could make parts or small parts.
The partners want guarantees of deliveries for twenty or thirty years, Dubsk<0xC3><0xBD> explains.
Last year, Czech Latecoere achieved a turnover of over 2.9 billion and a profit after tax of 147 million crowns.
The exclusive position among suppliers of aircraft manufacturers is not free of charge.
Latecoere has invested CZK 1.5 billion in Prague since 2000.
The company must have certificates of quality, certification of 170 special production processes and certificates of qualification for key employees.
Without them, the company would not have made any doors to aircraft.
To obtain certificates that the production processes meet the requirements of customers, and in repeated inspections, it costs millions of crowns to maintain them according to Dubsk<0xC3><0xBD>.
Production processes change every year.
They are more accurate and strict.
We need to train our employees, equip the equipment and certify the whole process again, Dubsk<0xC3><0xBD> adds.
The company is now finalizing a process for zinc and nickel plating to replace the previously harmful cadmium for human health.
They received the assignment from the manufacturer, but then they had to adapt the technology for the equipment or chemicals they use in Prague.
People from Boeing will come, check the concept of the entire line.
Then we show them the production.
They'll also check our lab.
They will test one set of samples themselves in their laboratory and then compare the results with ours, which shows Dubsk<0xC3><0xBD> the way customers control them.
The reward is the Prague company’s long-term exclusive contracts.
With the Prague plant today stands and falls the production of embraers.
For the A320, it produces half of the total door volume.
To replace the Czech Latecoere is either impossible for a Brazilian or European manufacturer, or very difficult.
However, this does not mean that you can say any price for the door.
Part of the contract is the price curve.
It tells you how much one door will cost ten, fifty, a hundred pieces made.
The price per piece continues to fall to a certain limit value.
We need to fit into this price pattern.
If not, we will lose, says Dubsk<0xC3><0xBD>.
Half of the hall, where electric cabinets for the military aircraft Airbus A400 M are assembled, is empty so far.
It is a symbol of the future.
Behind the screen, a new semi-robotic riveting and door assembly line for the A320 Neo is being built.
The riveting will be accelerated and refined.
"This is the trend that is moving away from the assembly in aviation," Dubsk<0xC3><0xBD> adds.
The future line is secure.
Airbus has ordered 3,278 A320s so far.
Just a few meters away, a line will be created for the complete installation of the doors for the upper deck of the A380.
This is a strategic decision of our parent company.
The aim is to shorten production times and reduce costs.
Full assembly could begin in two years, says Dubsk<0xC3><0xBD>.
However, before that, the company must pass qualification tests, for example, for the installation of some electrical and electronic devices in the doors of the largest Airbus.
