The researchers said that these worms are a great example of a new methodology called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart and muscle cells and is activated outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this method could one day replace deep brain stimulation — an invasive procedure in which electrodes that stimulate the brain are inserted into the patient’s brain.
The tubercles usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that the reaction occurs when placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
As he found out, the bubbles amplify the ultrasonic waves, which then pass through the body of the worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves act in the ion channels of TRP-4, which is found in the membranes of some worm cells.
