No one has explained to me how I should keep refugees in the country if they do not want to live in the Czech Republic.
Interior Minister Milan Chovanec (<0xC4><0x8C>SSD) complains after talks with his European counterparts that other Czech states are pushing for the adoption of quotas for the redistribution of refugees, but they refuse any discussion.
He also notes that no one has yet explained to him how he should keep allotted refugees in the Czech Republic if they do not want to live in our country anyway.
"We did not receive an answer, so we wanted the quotas to be dropped from the final text," Chovanec told reporters.
Can you describe more specifically the position with which you came to the meeting of the Ministers of the Interior and Foreign Affairs of the European Union?
We do not agree with mandatory quotas as with a system that simply cannot work.
We cannot speak of migrants as bags of salt or flour.
They are living beings who have some visions, they are going somewhere, they have some relatives.
We wanted to hear from our colleagues how we are able to keep migrants on the territory of the Member States if they are redistributed.
We can't imagine.
We did not receive an answer, and that is why we wanted the quotas to be deleted from the final text.
With other conclusions - functional hotspots, i.e. registration points, border protection, camps outside Europe, trust fund for African countries and other things, we have no problem with that.
We've been talking about this for a year now, and we say this is the way.
But to say that quotas will solve everything?
We've dealt with forty thousand recently, now it's a hundred and twenty thousand.
When will it be five hundred thousand?
How do we keep these people in the area?
Ninety-eight percent of all people who pass through us want to go to Germany.
Almost no one wants us, we just don't know how to keep them here.
Other foreigners, Ukrainians, Vietnamese and others who take the Czech Republic as their destination country, get asylum here, but the interest of people from this migration wave, that is, from Syria and other countries, is marginally close to zero.
You mentioned that the refugees don’t even want to come to us, but we have already committed 15 hundred people.
Wouldn't it be possible to take more of them this way?
We are committed to accepting 1,500 people, but on condition.
We said: functional hotspots, border protection, military operation.
Even for the 1,500, the point is that there will be 1,100 people with whom we will handle the asylum procedure.
They'll come to our detention facility and we'll treat them the same as the ones we picked up.
It is a big question, and we will debate this with Europe, whether we can detain people who will be registered in Italy and Greece, or Hungary.
Because Europe behaves in such a way that if they have registration, they cannot be detained.
That is, they will come to our territory with registration, and if there is an agreement, which is not yet, it may happen that even the 1100 will not be kept on the territory of the Czech Republic, and they will leave for Germany once they arrive.
If we can detain them during the asylum procedure, we will handle the asylum procedure with them.
If it is the citizens of Syria, Eritrea, almost 98 percent of the European statistics receive international protection.
Then they will receive documents that will allow them to travel around Europe.
And I think these people will end up in the target countries again.
Then there are four hundred people who are going to move.
This is the second project that is underway so far, and there we have only progressed in debating with the churches the possibility that they might be able to help them find jobs, accommodation, and so on.
But that's a very long run.
You said that the other states were not willing to discuss the ministerial meeting with us.
But isn’t it that the Czech Republic is simply rejecting quotas, but is not offering any solidarity step that would unblock the discussion?
And what exactly do you think this is a solidarity move?
If the Federal Republic of Germany gives the impetus that all migrants from Syria can come to them, then the news spreads in the order of hours throughout all the camps in Europe, but also in Turkey, Jordan.
This invites another migration wave that is heading for Germany because they simply do not want to come to us.
We think the way is to protect the external borders - simply deter those migration waves, help the needy, and separate economic migrants.
Clearly let them know they don’t stand a chance.
Last year alone, 50,000 Kosovans came to Germany.
From a safe Kosovo, where we pay for all the saturation of this state, including the police, the courts, the public prosecutor's offices.
If we were to separate them and not accept them or only accept them according to the needs of the economies, the fifty percent of what social systems give them in vain today could go to refugees.
Compared to the first day that Germany introduced controls, the number of detainees in the Czech Republic jumped.
Now it's eighty, the first day it was twelve.
How far is it going to go to tighten border controls?
We were afraid of catching hundreds of people.
These are the numbers we manage.
We still have a few hundred vacancies in stone detention facilities.
Of course, all the people we detain will be returned to Austria within seven days.
We do it as standard.
The Austrians are the only ones who take these people away from us, it is complicated with Hungary and the Greeks - this is a completely useless story.
Where is the breaking point?
Would it have to be a thousand a day?
I think it would have to be a few hundred a day.
Two hundred, three hundred people a day, two, three days in a row, our capacity will be exhausted enough to trigger crisis plans.
Then I agreed with the Prime Minister that he would immediately convene an extraordinary government.
He is very interested in the whole thing, we are several times a day in telephone contact.
If the situation were to arise, the government could sit down in fact immediately, and with one resolution it would decide to strengthen the police by an army, say a customs administration, or a prison service.
The extreme variant is the state of emergency that Hungary has now declared in some places?
I don't think we can get this far.
Be aware that our position is different, we are a national state within Europe, we have a Schengen border only and only at the airport.
I do not know what would have to happen in order for this to happen on the territory of the Czech Republic, I do not want to spread alarm information.
All the information we have, whether from Moldova, Serbia, Hungary, suggests rather that the Hungarians will try to divert the migration flow to Croatia and Slovenia, which would then mean a direct route to Austria.
The Czech Republic would be affected very marginally, almost at all.
