At its most anticipated meeting in years, federal reserve lawmakers will spend two days this week seated at a 27-foot-long Honduran mahogany table and decide whether it’s time to raise the key interest rate after nearly a decade.
Standing above them at one end of a central bank ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a wall painting of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are to put the economic interests of the nation above everything else.
The central bank has a dual charge from Congress: maximizing U.S. employment and keeping prices stable.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be an X-factor in too close to a predictable decision to be announced on Thursday on whether the U.S. economy is ready to kick-start while weaning off an unprecedented stimulus in the form of near-zero short-term interest rates on the ground since the end of 2008.
Although most of the data shows solid economic growth, recent turbulence in global financial markets could already scare the cautious Fed into adding to volatility by raising its federal funds benchmark rate – and that’s no more than a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing to watch first,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think they were just looking for an excuse to not increase the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already provides them with sufficient reason to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is the cause of nervousness in the financial markets.
About half of the economists recently interviewed by Blomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to hold off on the issue, with a key indicator of only about 30% chance of an increase.
This would indicate a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises rates, only if politicians soften the decline by promising that a further increase is not in sight.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average jumped by 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,598.85.
The meeting was triggered by the expectation that Fed politicians will hold rates steady this week, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be a surprise if the Fed now raises rates,” he said.
If the Fed’s politicians did, “they would have to go to the extreme in their program statement and hold hands with the financial markets so they don’t panic.”
Other experts argued that raising rates would calm financial markets, as it would remove uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects rates to rise this year through spring and early summer despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
While job creation slowed in August, the labour market saw solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% in the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage earnings showed signs of lifting.
And while inflation continues to run below the central bank’s annual 2% target, Fed policymakers say the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tightness of the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to tumble at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell by as much as 16 percent below its record value in May as investors feared a slowing Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has bounced somewhat this month, and the Dow is now only losing nearly 10% of its May high.
The uneasy market situation provides the Fed with a complex calculation of when to start raising the interest rate.
“In the absence of what has happened in the financial markets and reports of the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, there would be a tightening at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior researcher at UCLA’s Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now he predicts that they will wait at least a month to gain better control of the consequences.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about how this will affect the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data to rely on about the latest developments in China,” Oliner said.
The health status of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s main interests, so technically it should not be included in their decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the entire world.
The impact of the central bank in recent years has been enormous.
A mere hint by then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “abuse” their monetary expansion in the market has triggered convulsions around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interconnected, Fed officials can be expected to follow developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central bankers and experts to better read the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global wealth-management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., noted this month that “the Fed has a history of exaggerated with movements in financial markets that seem unrelated to economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee's policy making that pushed for higher rates, cited the decision in 1998-99 as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia has led the Fed to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75 percentage points during three sessions "despite the limited identifiable impacts on U.S. growth," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed these cuts.
The Fed should only prioritize financial stability concerns during the Great Depression, such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam Posen S., a former member of the Bank of England’s rate-setting committee.
The latest bustle is not even approaching this level, he said.
“You certainly don’t want to be in a situation of fear of rising rates because markets are upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a double mandate and doesn't mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should get to the top.
