After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c level dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the drug-treated group, this value remained at about 8%.
But this better “glycemic control” — reflected in better levels of hemoglobin A1c — did not reduce mortality in five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared average results with two types of operations.
After the fifth year, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastrectomy group (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), achieved greater reductions in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent versus 2.1 percent), and were more likely to have diabetes remission (46.9 percent versus 16.7 percent).
While the new study does not show an improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden where they found that surgery leads to life extension, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
