In the event of bankruptcy of the CK, insurance companies have to pay the claims of clients in full.
Insurance companies should pay the claims of clients in case of bankruptcy of the travel agency in full.
The House of Commons decided on Wednesday when it approved a revised amendment to the Act on the Conditions of Business in Tourism.
Travel agencies will be able to replace bankruptcy insurance with a bank guarantee, according to the draft, which will be sent to the Senate for consideration.
Insurance companies do not agree with the obligation to pay the claims of clients even above the agreed limit.
The Ministry of Regional Development insists on the adjustment, argues consumer protection.
Insurance companies have already threatened to end insurance of travel agencies against the crash, if the amendment will apply.
The proposal has also been criticised by travel agencies.
Without insurance, they will either have to leave or leave the country.
Minister of Regional Development Karla <0xC5><0xA0>lechtov<0xC3><0xA1> (for ANO) pointed out that cases where insurance companies did not pay full compensation are not Euro-comform.
She drew attention to this year's decision of the Constitutional Court, which confirmed that the client is entitled to a full refund regardless of the insurance limit.
Insurance companies will receive enough information about the management of travel agencies and will be able to determine the right limit, <0xC5><0xA0>lechtov<0xC3><0xA1> said.
"We appreciate the efforts to increase consumer protection, but it must have such a limit that it is feasible," said Miroslav Kalousek, Vice-President of TOP 09.
The bank guarantee will not work because no one will give it unlimited.
“Travel agencies will have to stop their activities or move abroad,” Kalousek warned.
A member of the Presidium of the Association of Czech Travel Agencies Tomio Okamura (SPD) disagreed with Kalousk’s concerns on the basis of a survey among members of the CK.
"Stop lobbying the insurance companies," he said.
The statements of the insurance companies do not consider Okamura to be relevant, there is no official written statement of them in this sense, according to him.
However, they are investigating whether travel agencies will make a contribution, which, according to Okamura, is not a problem.
Jana Fischerov<0xC3><0xA1> (ODS), who referred to the opinion of the competing Association of Travel Agencies of the Czech Republic, and her party colleague Petr Bendl, who spoke about lubricating the stairs to Czech travel agencies, also warned against the provision.
According to Fischer, travel agencies will not be able to negotiate insurance.
“Consumer protection works,” says Fischer.
The House did not approve of her proposal to release the disputed passage.
Vojt<0xC4><0x9B>ch Filip (KS<0xC4><0x8C>M) also did not come forward with a proposal to return the draft to the committee due to an alleged violation of the Civil Code.
Filip pointed to travel agencies that he said could endanger consumers.
The rapporteur of the draft, Martina Berdychov<0xC3><0xA1> (ANO), in view of the verdict of the Constitutional Court, withdrew her proposal, which would limit the liability of insurance companies in cases where they could not know that the insurance performance would not cover the entire risk.
The novel will not initially propose a minimum insurance limit of four million for travel agencies offering air travel and a limit of one million for offices selling, for example, bus travel.
The limit will remain at 30 percent of the planned sales of tours.
However, the insurance performance limit will have to be such that, in the event of a travel agency’s bankruptcy, it covers all the claims of the customers.
Even after adjustments, the standard stipulates that travel agencies will have to re-indicate which travel agency organises the tour for the tours sold.
Travel agencies will have to provide insurance companies before concluding the contract, among other things, data on the management and the number of trips.
The approved amendment of the Public Administration Committee also envisages further regular information of insurance undertakings.
Travel agencies will have to provide them with monthly data on the number of passengers and trips sold, the total price of trips sold, and the amount of travel advances and sales and vouchers.
If the Ministry of Regional Development finds that the travel agency has failed to comply with any of the legal obligations towards the insurance company, it will call on the insurance company to rectify it or will be able to prohibit it from entering into new contracts in the event that the breach of the obligation could jeopardize the interests of customers.
The amendment is also intended to re-adjust the financing of the mountain service.
The Ministry of Regional Development will determine the amount of the subsidy to the mountain service on the basis of its application, which will always be submitted by the end of April for the next year.
The application will include a report on the use of state funds in the past year, a financial plan of expenditure and a outlook for the next two years.
According to the association, the lawmaker did not think of the situation that would occur if the insurance company terminated the CK contract.
It will not be allowed to organize trips and clients who bought the trip before the cancellation of the insurance will lose it according to the association.
In such a case, the CK will suffer a significant loss and may even go bankrupt, even though its management was in good condition.
One way that travel agencies can deal with this situation will be to sue the State for compensation.
Another option will be to go abroad and use much softer conditions abroad, and then we will operate on our market only as agencies, said the vice-president of the association, Jan Pape<0xC5><0xBE>.
According to him, the draft amendment also contains the institute of bank guarantee, but so ill-considered that it cannot be implemented in practice at all, since the bank guarantee cannot sound for an unlimited amount.
Moreover, according to the Association, a change in the current practice is de facto useless.
Within two years, the whole law will have to be recast in view of the new EU directive.
A total of 942 active insured travel agencies are currently operating on the Czech market.
This year, only three CCs have ceased operations.
Domestic travel agencies sell tours worth about 20 billion CZK per year.
