Xi Calls for Opening the Economy to the Wider World
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with Tuesday's governance reform.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies," he said about the 16th session of the central head of the group to deepen the overall reform.
Promoting opening-up in emerging reforms will give new impetus and vitality, and will also provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Steering Group has adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, the easing of border control policies, support for state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital and the reorganisation of the registration resident system.
The declaration states that a negative list will be drawn up to identify sectors and businesses that are outside investment limits.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through test programmes.
This step is significant because it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open.
The government will also release controls on the powers it delegates to companies and make sure that the companies themselves decide how to run their businesses.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to support regional growth.
In an effort to open up a state-controlled sector, more areas will be opened up to private investment.
“The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of companies that are financed from abroad and will provide them with better services,” the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a "green card" by optimizing the requirements and simplifying the application process.
Ensuring the right of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at the meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
In the Karlovy Vary region, new bed divisions may be established.
According to Jakub P<0xC3><0xA1>nik (<0xC4><0x8C>SSD), the current capacity of the wards of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient, and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the wards of individual hospitals.
There are also opportunities to expand care in the area.
For example, in the department of surgical departments, one-day surgery centers could be established, where, according to the established concept, surgical procedures would be performed that do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours.
What specific hospitals should have a one-day surgery-focused workplace is not yet clear.
At the skin department of the Karlovy Vary hospital, a laser center could be created with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases.
The concept also recommended the creation of an apalic center to care for patients with brain disorders who are in a vegetative state.
Such a center should be established centrally and should be an integral part of the anesthesiological and resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a facility to the Ostrov hospital, where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity, which appears to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary region, are the beds of follow-up care, especially the beds of the long-term ill (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and, above all, should closely follow the beds of acute care.
Part of this facility should function as a rehabilitation bed and part as a classic LDN bed, the concept recommends.
As he points out, aftercare beds are missing mainly in the Karlovy Vary hospital.
This is where abandoned buildings could be used after centralization.
Last but not least, in the Karlovy Vary region there are no social health beds with a focus on the treatment of Alzheimer’s disease.
There is a shortage of these beds in the entire republic, so it could also serve as a so-called Alzheimer's center for other regions.
According to the recommendations, hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-up beds, for which funds from European subsidies will be released.
"These are beds that will follow the fields of specialised care and will create space for the translation of patients after surgery, for example, after cardiosurgical, neurosurgical, transplantation or other procedures," the regional concept of bed care describes.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.
